In article <CAp3LC.502@rahul.net>, dhesi@rahul.net (Rahul Dhesi) writes:
> In <22sbt6INN4sc@twain.ucs.umass.edu> quilty@twain.ucs.umass.edu (Lulu
> of the lotus-eaters) writes:
> 
> >>Would it be feasible for a writer to send an MD5 hash product to a trusted
> >>individual or service...
> 
> >It would also, presumably, be possible simply to publish a hash as a
> >classified ad in a newspaper.
> 
> I understand that not only does Bellcore do this every week, but that
> it claims a patent on this technique.  The hash code published is a
> composite of a number of hash codes, each for a different document.

The technique that Bellcore has patented involves using the output
from the previous hash as one of the inputs to the next hash.  That
provides an unforgeable sequence of hash values, and hence of documents,
which is linked to reality by the newspaper ads.  See

@inproceedings{timestamp1,
        author = {S. Haber and W.S. Stornetta},
        title = {How to Time-Stamp a Digital Document},
        booktitle = {Advances in Cryptology: Proceedings of {CRYPTO} '90},
        publisher = {Springer-Verlag},
        year = 1991,
}

@article{timestamp2,
        author = {S. Haber and W.S. Stornetta},
        title = {How to Time-Stamp a Digital Document},
